		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2015"></a><br><code>sle2015/paper14</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>Parsing expression grammars made practical</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NicolasLaurent.html">Nicolas Laurent</a>, <a href="../profile/KimMens.html">Kim Mens</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814265">10.1145/2814251.2814265</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper advances PEGs as a grammar formalism (a meta-language) and focuses on making PEG-based parsing practical.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It discusses language-definition choices (syntax and disambiguation) enabled by PEGs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> PEG properties such as closure under composition connect directly to modular composition of syntactic fragments.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> Because PEGs define recursive-descent parsers, the work is tied to runtime parsing/interpretation techniques.
</li></ul></li></ul>
